& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Intimal sarcomas of the pulmonary artery and aorta are rare entities with a poor prognosis. In many instances, pulmonary artery sarcomas are misinterpreted as acute or chronic pulmonary thromboembolism, whereas aortic intimal sarcomas are often misdiagnosed as protuberant atherosclerotic disease or intimal thrombus. Discernment of intimal sarcomas from these and other common benign entities is essential for the timely initiation of aggressive therapy. The most useful imaging modalities for assessment of a suspected intimal sarcoma include CT angiography, fluorine 18–fluorodeoxyglucose PET, and MRI. The authors discuss the clinical features, current treatment options, characteristic imaging findings, and underlying pathologic features of intimal sarcomas. The authors emphasize imaging discernment of intimal sarcomas and how their differential diagnosis is informed by knowledge of radiologic-pathologic correlation. The most reliable distinguishing imaging features are also emphasized to improve accurate and timely diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200184">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200184">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Composite shows PAS differential diagnosis. A, Acute saddle pulmonary embolism (PE). Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows central filling defects that have thin ropey features compared with the asymmetric masslike appearance of PAS. B, Chronic thromboembolism. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large filling defect that eclipses the lumen, with acute angles to the vessel wall; PAS was initially suspected and excluded. C, D, Tumor thromboembolism, uterine sarcoma. C, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a masslike filling defect with soft-tissue attenuation in the main PA that mimics PAS. D, Sagittal steady-state free precession MR image in the same patient as in C shows involvement of the right ventricular outflow tract, another feature shared with PAS. E, F, Fibrosing mediastinitis owing to histoplasmosis. E, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a lobulated filling defect in the right PA, which represents thrombus formation secondary to extrinsic compression. Note the calcified nodes of healed granulomatous disease. F, Axial fluorine-18 (18F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) PET/CT image in the same patient as in E shows no FDG uptake. Contrast-enhanced MR images (not shown) helped confirm that there was no enhancement."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig1.jpeg" height="1933" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Composite shows PAS differential diagnosis. <i>A,</i> Acute saddle pulmonary embolism (PE). Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows central filling defects that have thin ropey features compared with the asymmetric masslike appearance of PAS. <i>B,</i> Chronic thromboembolism. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large filling defect that eclipses the lumen, with acute angles to the vessel wall; PAS was initially suspected and excluded. <i>C, D,</i> Tumor thromboembolism, uterine sarcoma. <i>C,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a masslike filling defect with soft-tissue attenuation in the main PA that mimics PAS. <i>D,</i> Sagittal steady-state free precession MR image in the same patient as in <i>C</i> shows involvement of the right ventricular outflow tract, another feature shared with PAS. <i>E, F,</i> Fibrosing mediastinitis owing to histoplasmosis. <i>E,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a lobulated filling defect in the right PA, which represents thrombus formation secondary to extrinsic compression. Note the calcified nodes of healed granulomatous disease. <i>F,</i> Axial fluorine-18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) PET/CT image in the same patient as in <i>E</i> shows no FDG uptake. Contrast-enhanced MR images (not shown) helped confirm that there was no enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Composite shows AIS differential diagnosis. A, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows prominent atheroma and organized intimal thrombus in the aneurysmal descending thoracic aorta lined by calcified plaque. B, Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows prominent atheroma and intimal thrombus, atherosclerotic abdominal aortic aneurysm. AIS is more likely to have lobulated, thick, or “shaggy” endoluminal margins; adjacent calcified plaque is unusual. C, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a “floating” intimal thrombus in the aortic arch, with intermediate attenuation and punctate calcification. D, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a floating intimal thrombus in the aortic arch, with uniform low attenuation. Early AIS may mimic focal intimal thrombus. E, Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows Takayasu aortitis, with segmental wall thickening of the descending aorta, lined with punctate calcification. Aortitis can produce smooth wall thickening but without endoluminal components, in contrast to that of AIS. F, Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows bacterial aortitis, with a focal penetrating aneurysm in the descending thoracic aorta, an unusual but reported appearance of AIS."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig2.jpeg" height="2123" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Composite shows AIS differential diagnosis. <i>A,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows prominent atheroma and organized intimal thrombus in the aneurysmal descending thoracic aorta lined by calcified plaque. <i>B,</i> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows prominent atheroma and intimal thrombus, atherosclerotic abdominal aortic aneurysm. AIS is more likely to have lobulated, thick, or “shaggy” endoluminal margins; adjacent calcified plaque is unusual. <i>C,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a “floating” intimal thrombus in the aortic arch, with intermediate attenuation and punctate calcification. <i>D,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a floating intimal thrombus in the aortic arch, with uniform low attenuation. Early AIS may mimic focal intimal thrombus. <i>E,</i> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows Takayasu aortitis, with segmental wall thickening of the descending aorta, lined with punctate calcification. Aortitis can produce smooth wall thickening but without endoluminal components, in contrast to that of AIS. <i>F,</i> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows bacterial aortitis, with a focal penetrating aneurysm in the descending thoracic aorta, an unusual but reported appearance of AIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. (a) Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. (b) Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. (c) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig3a.jpeg" height="1250" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. <b>(b)</b> Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. (a) Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. (b) Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. (c) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig3b.jpeg" height="1403" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. <b>(b)</b> Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. (a) Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. (b) Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. (c) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig3c.jpeg" height="1250" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. PAS manifesting 2 years after an initial misdiagnosis as PE in a 78-year-old man who was a retired physician. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram obtained at initial presentation shows a small broad-based filling defect (arrow) in the left main PA. <b>(b)</b> Frontal chest radiograph obtained 2 years later shows a left-sided mediastinal contour abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing mass centered in the left pulmonary artery (LPA) (*), with left hilar and mediastinal invasion (arrowheads). Note the left pleural effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4a.jpeg" height="1053" width="1470" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4b.jpeg" height="1053" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4c.jpeg" height="1136" width="1359" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4d.jpeg" height="1136" width="1591" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4e.jpeg" height="1226" width="1710" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4f" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4f.jpeg" height="1226" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig4f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4f</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4g" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). (a–c) Axial (a), coronal (b), and oblique sagittal (c) reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in a and b), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in c). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in c is artifactual. (d, e) Axial (d) and coronal (e) fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. (f) Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. (g) Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig4g.jpeg" height="1688" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig4g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4g</span>. PAS with extensive peripheral vascular involvement in a 43-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 1 month earlier, with no clinical or radiologic response to anticoagulation therapy (histologic specimen is depicted in Fig E1f). <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and oblique sagittal <b>(c)</b> reconstructions from CT angiographic maximum intensity projections (MIPs) show a broad-based filling defect in the LPA (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), with additional tumor filling the left upper and lower lobar arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). The left lower lobe peripheral opacity likely represents evolving ischemia. The focal hyperattenuation in the interventricular septum in <b>c</b> is artifactual. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> fused FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the LPA and its branches. <b>(f)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (5-second delay) shows obstructed perfusion (arrow) to the LPA and its branches. <b>(g)</b> Photograph of the left pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the left lobar arterial branches (arrows). The PAS (*) in the LPA was resected intraoperatively before lung removal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig4g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated d-dimer levels. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. (c) Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. (d) Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. (e) Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig5a.jpeg" height="1129" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-dimer levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. <b>(c)</b> Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated d-dimer levels. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. (c) Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. (d) Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. (e) Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig5b.jpeg" height="1129" width="988" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-dimer levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. <b>(c)</b> Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated d-dimer levels. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. (c) Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the pr