ving the PV. (c) Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. (d) Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. (e) Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig5d.jpeg" height="1199" width="856" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-dimer levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. <b>(c)</b> Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5e" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated d-dimer levels. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. (c) Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. (d) Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. (e) Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig5e.jpeg" height="1199" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig5e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5e</span>. PAS with involvement of the pulmonary valve (PV) in a 43-year-old woman who is a smoker with slowly progressive dyspnea over 3 months, tachycardia, and elevated <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-dimer levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large broad-based filling defect in the right pulmonary artery (RPA). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a second irregularly marginated filling defect (*) involving the PV. <b>(c)</b> Frontal pulmonary arteriogram shows contrast material cut-off (arrow) in the proximal RPA. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of an autopsy specimen of the heart opened at the pulmonary outlet shows tumor (circle) inseparable from the PV. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the right pneumonectomy specimen shows yellow tumor distending the perihilar pulmonary arterial branches (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig5e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. (a) Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. (c) Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig6a.jpeg" height="1167" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. (a) Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. (c) Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig6b.jpeg" height="1252" width="1754" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. (a) Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. (c) Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig6c.jpeg" height="1252" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. PAS with tubular morphology in a 21-year-old man with pleuritic chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiograms of the PV and main PA show an intravascular mass (*) with mobility during the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated tubular intravascular filling defect, without broad intimal attachment. The linear high-attenuation areas likely correspond to vascular channels within the lesion. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected specimen shows a tubular mass (arrow) with a narrow base of attachment to the PV (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. (a) Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. (c) Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. (d) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. (e) Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). (f) Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig7a.jpeg" height="898" width="1257" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. <b>(e)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). <b>(f)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. (a) Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right 