pacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. (d) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. (e) Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). (f) Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig7d.jpeg" height="1007" width="717" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. <b>(e)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). <b>(f)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain).<div class="core