lar branches. <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. <b>(e)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). <b>(f)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7f" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. (a) Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. (c) Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. (d) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. (e) Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). (f) Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig7f.jpeg" height="1007" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig7f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7f</span>. PAS with intralobar extension and pulmonary infarct in a 45-year-old woman, diagnosed with PE 4 months earlier, with persistent dyspnea despite anticoagulation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a large filling defect crossing the PA bifurcation and filling the RPA and proximal vascular branches. <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows right heart strain, with dilatation of the right heart chambers and flattening of the interventricular septum. Small right pleural effusion is present. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (MIP reformation, lung window) shows a peripheral wedge-shaped ground-glass opacity in right upper lobe (arrowhead), compatible with infarct. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows tumor filling the RPA (*), with contiguous involvement of several vascular branches. <b>(e)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows tumor filling an intrapulmonary artery (*) (hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain). <b>(f)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows subpleural pulmonary infarction (*), a discrete zone of lung parenchyma with nearly invisible alveolar structures, and poor staining characteristics owing to ischemic necrosis (H-E stain).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig7f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with contiguous extension into lobar branches of the main RPA in a 69-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 3 months earlier, with no clinical improvement with anticoagulation therapy (gross specimen is depicted in Fig E1d). (a) Axial CT pulmonary angiographic image shows a large filling defect in the RPA, with a lobulated margin. The vessel appears expanded and nearly eclipsed. (b) Axial fused PET/CT image shows patchy tracer uptake within the filling defect. (c) Nuclear medicine V/Q image (anterior projection) shows absent perfusion to the right lung. (d) Coronal CT pulmonary angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a broad-based near-occlusive filling defect in the dilated RPA, with extension into the right upper lobar arteries. Subtle intralesional contrast enhancement is evident. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous intralesional delayed enhancement."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig8a.jpeg" height="1054" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. PAS with contiguous extension into lobar branches of the main RPA in a 69-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 3 months earlier, with no clinical improvement with anticoagulation therapy (gross specimen is depicted in Fig E1d). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiographic image shows a large filling defect in the RPA, with a lobulated margin. The vessel appears expanded and nearly eclipsed. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows patchy tracer uptake within the filling defect. <b>(c)</b> Nuclear medicine V/Q image (anterior projection) shows absent perfusion to the right lung. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT pulmonary angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a broad-based near-occlusive filling defect in the dilated RPA, with extension into