e filling defect. (c) Nuclear medicine V/Q image (anterior projection) shows absent perfusion to the right lung. (d) Coronal CT pulmonary angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a broad-based near-occlusive filling defect in the dilated RPA, with extension into the right upper lobar arteries. Subtle intralesional contrast enhancement is evident. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous intralesional delayed enhancement."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig8e.jpeg" height="1071" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. PAS with contiguous extension into lobar branches of the main RPA in a 69-year-old man who was diagnosed with PE 3 months earlier, with no clinical improvement with anticoagulation therapy (gross specimen is depicted in Fig E1d). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiographic image shows a large filling defect in the RPA, with a lobulated margin. The vessel appears expanded and nearly eclipsed. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows patchy tracer uptake within the filling defect. <b>(c)</b> Nuclear medicine V/Q image (anterior projection) shows absent perfusion to the right lung. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT pulmonary angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows a broad-based near-occlusive filling defect in the dilated RPA, with extension into the right upper lobar arteries. Subtle intralesional contrast enhancement is evident. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous intralesional delayed enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. (b) Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. (c) Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. (d) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. (e) Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig9a.jpeg" height="1054" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. (b) Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. (c) Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. (d) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. (e) Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig9b.jpeg" height="952" width="1143" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure