terectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. (b) Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. (c) Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. (d) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. (e) Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig9d.jpeg" height="952" width="1333" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. (b) Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. (c) Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. (d) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. (e) Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig9e.jpeg" height="1054" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. PAS mimics saddle embolus in a 45-year-old woman who presented with hemoptysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows near-complete occlusion of the main and proximal RPA by an intravascular lesion. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image confirms near-complete occlusion of the central PAs, with a filling defect extending into the right and left PAs and their branches (*). Note the moderate-sized pericardial effusion. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows marginal radiotracer uptake in the lesion and intense focal uptake near the PV. <b>(d)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows contrast material accumulation, chiefly at the margins of the intravascular mass. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of a pulmonary endarterectomy specimen shows a mixed gelatinous and soft-tissue mass extracted from the main PA and PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with polypoid morphology and retrograde involvement of the right heart in a 76-year-old woman with chest discomfort and palpitations (additional histology is depicted in Fig E1b). (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a heterogeneous filling defect at the PA bifurcation and dilatation of the main PA. (b) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows that the filling defect further involves the PV and right ventricle. Additional images (not shown) helped confirm further extension into the right atrium. (c) Sagittal CT angiographic image centered in the right hemithorax shows low-attenuation filling defects in multiple intralobar arteries (arrowheads). (d) Low-power photomicrograph of the tumor near the tricuspid valve (TV) shows filiform projections with myxoid features (*) (hematoxylin-eosin stain)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig10a.jpeg" height="1077" width="1499" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. PAS with polypoid morphology and retrograde involvement of the right heart in a 76-year-old woman with chest discomfort and palpitations (additional histology is depicted in Fig E1b). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a heterogeneous filling defect at the PA bifurcation and dilatation of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows that the filling defect further involves the PV and right ventricle. Additional images (not shown) helped confirm further extension into the right atrium. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image centered in the right hemithorax shows low-attenuation filling defects in multiple intralobar arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of the tumor near the tricuspid valve <i>(TV)</i> shows filiform projections with myxoid features (*) (hematoxylin-eosin stain).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with polypoid morphology and retrograde involvement of the right heart in a 76-year-old woman with chest discomfort and palpitations (additional histology is depicted in Fig E1b). (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a heterogeneous filling defect at the PA bifurcation and dilatation of the main PA. (b) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows that the filling defect further involves the PV and right ventricle. Additional images (not shown) helped confirm further extension into the right atrium. (c) Sagittal CT angiographic image centered in the right hemithorax shows low-attenuation filling defects in multiple intralobar arteries (arrowheads). (d) Low-power photomicrograph of the tumor near the tricuspid valve (TV) shows filiform projections with myxoid features (*) (hematoxylin-eosin stain)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig10b.jpeg" height="1592" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. PAS with polypoid morphology and retrograde involvement of the right heart in a 76-year-old woma