mg src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig10d.jpeg" height="1502" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. PAS with polypoid morphology and retrograde involvement of the right heart in a 76-year-old woman with chest discomfort and palpitations (additional histology is depicted in Fig E1b). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a heterogeneous filling defect at the PA bifurcation and dilatation of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows that the filling defect further involves the PV and right ventricle. Additional images (not shown) helped confirm further extension into the right atrium. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image centered in the right hemithorax shows low-attenuation filling defects in multiple intralobar arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of the tumor near the tricuspid valve <i>(TV)</i> shows filiform projections with myxoid features (*) (hematoxylin-eosin stain).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. (b) Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). (c) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. (d) Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig11a.jpeg" height="1124" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. (a) Axial CT ang