gure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. (b) Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). (c) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. (d) Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig11c.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic" aria-label="PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. (b) Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). (c) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. (d) Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig11d.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. PAS with multiple cavitary lung lesions compatible with tumoral infarcts in a 38-year-old woman who was a smoker with gradual-onset pleuritic chest pain and new tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a filling defect in the distal left main PA and left upper lobar PA, as well as a peripheral cavitary consolidation in the left upper lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image (lung window) shows peripheral left upper lobe cavitary consolidation. Additional cavitary subpleural lesions are present in other lobes (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows two components of intravascular tumor (arrowheads) in the LPA and involving the PV, both with marginal enhancement. Moderate-sized left pleural effusion is present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of left pneumonectomy specimen shows the cross section of the LPA with extrusion of a multilobulated polypoid gelatinous tumor (arrowheads). The margin of the surgical incision (arrow) of the LPA is well depicted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. (a) Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). (b) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. (c) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. (d) Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig12a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. (a) Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). (b) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. (c) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. (d) Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig12b.jpeg" height="1331" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic" aria-label="PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. (a) Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). (b) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. (c) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. (d) Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig12c.jpeg" height="1331" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic" aria-label="PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. (a) Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). (b) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. (c) CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. (d) Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig12d.jpeg" height="1331" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. PA osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 48-year-old woman who presented with syncope and progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiac silhouette enlargement and lobulated calcification overlying the aorto-pulmonic window (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows a partly calcified mass (arrow) within the main PA near the PV. Note the bronchial arterial collaterals (arrowhead), suggestive of a subacute or chronic pathologic condition. <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic image (coned axial view) shows massive dilatation of the right heart chambers (*) and flattening of the interventricular septum (arrowhead), compatible with strain. Pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and dependent left lower lobe consolidation are also present. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected opened main PA shows an intravascular pale mass with a firm glistening white “bony” component (*). The mass molds to the main PA (and proximal LPA) lumen and arises from the PV by a membranous stalk (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. (b) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. (c) Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig13a.jpeg" height="1125" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. <b>(c)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. (b) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. (c) Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig13b.jpeg" height="1125" width="593" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. <b>(c)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. (a) Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. (b) Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. (c) Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig13c.jpeg" height="1125" width="1528" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. PA chondroblastic osteosarcoma, an unusual variant of PAS, in a 63-year-old woman with persistent chest pain despite anticoagulation therapy for presumed PE. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a broad-based filling defect in the RPA, containing internal high-attenuation foci. CTED with dystrophic calcifications was initially suspected. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a right pneumonectomy specimen shows multiple intralobar arteries expanded by an intravascular tumor (arrows), with glistening white foci. <b>(c)</b> Medium-power photomicrograph shows a cellular neoplasm composed of pleomorphic ovoid spindled cells, with prominent nucleoli (hematoxylin-eosin stain). The diagnosis of osteosarcoma was established by the presence of osteoid matrix (arrowheads), the homogeneous pink material, along with the foci of calcified mineralization (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14a.jpeg" height="1627" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14b.jpeg" height="1077" width="770" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14c.jpeg" height="1627" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14d.jpeg" height="1077" width="1078" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14e" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14e.jpeg" height="1627" width="1456" aria-labelledby="fig14e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14e</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14f" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. (a) Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. (b, c) Fused axial (b) and sagittal (c) FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. (d) Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). (e) Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). (f) Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig14f.jpeg" height="1077" width="770" aria-labelledby="fig14f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14f</span>. AIS misdiagnosed preoperatively as a massive fibrofatty intimal atheroma in a 58-year-old man with intermittent chest pain over the past several months. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT angiographic image shows an elongated intraluminal filling defect with shaggy margins, located in the transverse and descending thoracic aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Fused axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> FDG PET/CT images show radiotracer uptake within the aortic filling defect, adrenal glands, and intra-abdominal lymph nodes. <b>(d)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image shows that the lesion occludes at least 50% of the aortic lumen (*). <b>(e)</b> Coronal CT angiographic image (MIP reformation) shows that the lesion (arrowheads) involves most of the descending thoracic aorta but spares the lower thoracic and upper abdominal aorta (*). <b>(f)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced head CT image obtained for mental status changes 1 month later shows two hyperattenuating intra-axial mass lesions (*) and surrounding vasogenic edema in the left temporal and right occipital lobes, compatible with embolic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig14f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. (a) Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. (c) Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. (d) Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig15a.jpeg" height="1544" width="1543" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. <b>(a)</b> Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. <b>(c)</b> Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. (a) Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. (c) Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. (d) Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig15b.jpeg" height="1544" width="1103" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. <b>(a)</b> Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. <b>(c)</b> Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. (a) Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. (c) Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. (d) Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig15c.jpeg" height="1700" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. <b>(a)</b> Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. <b>(c)</b> Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic" aria-label="AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. (a) Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). (b) Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. (c) Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. (d) Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig15d.jpeg" height="750" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. AIS manifesting with systemic embolism in a 61-year-old woman with acute onset of painful cold right foot and a history of mesenteric ischemia attributed to aortic thrombus, per her medical record. <b>(a)</b> Oblique sagittal chest CT angiographic image shows a protuberant intraluminal aortic mass (*) in the descending thoracic aorta (which was enlarged compared with that depicted on CT images obtained several months earlier). Note the adjacent irregularly contoured intimal thickening (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial gated CT angiographic image (coned down) shows an eccentric intraluminal mass (arrow), with a shaggy luminal margin. <b>(c)</b> Coronal bilateral lower extremity angiogram (MIP) shows cut-off of contrast material flow in the right-sided tibial vessels (arrowhead), without distal collateral flow. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the resected thoracic aorta, open intimal surface, shows a lobulated gelatinous lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Characteristic histologic features of the two most common patterns of intimal sarcomas. A, Illustration shows a cellular pattern, characteristic of PAS. A polypoid intimal lesion projects into the lumen, composed of tumor cells on the spectrum of myxoid, spindled, and epithelioid features. Limited vascularity (V) and scattered areas of the myxoid matrix (acellular proteoglycan material elaborated by the tumor itself) are present. Limited foci of osteosarcoma and chondrosarcoma are also possible. Limited fibrin may coat the tumor surface (arrowheads). B, Illustration shows a fibrin layering pattern, characteristic of AIS. There is a thick broad-based lesion composed of avascular fibrin intermixed with necrotic tissue. This polypoid endoluminal mass has a superficial coating of tumor cells (arrowheads) that arise directly from the intima at the tapered edges (arrows) of the lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200184/asset/images/large/rg.2021200184.fig16.jpeg" height="1529" width="1792" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Characteristic histologic features of the two most common patterns of intimal sarcomas. <i>A,</i> Illustration shows a cellular pattern, characteristic of PAS. A polypoid intimal lesion projects into the lumen, composed of tumor cells on the spectrum of myxoid, spindled, and epithelioid features. Limited vascularity <i>(V)</i> and scattered areas of the myxoid matrix (acellular proteoglycan material elaborated by the tumor itself) are present. Limited foci of osteosarcoma and chondrosarcoma are also possible. Limited fibrin may coat the tumor surface (arrowheads). <i>B,</i> Illustration shows a fibrin layering pattern, characteristic of AIS. There is a thick broad-based lesion composed of avascular fibrin intermixed with necrotic tissue. This polypoid endoluminal mass has a superficial coating of tumor cells (arrowheads) that arise directly from the intima at the tapered edges (arrows) of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200184&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Krüger I, Borowski A, Horst M, de Vivie ER, Theissen P, Gross-Fengels W. Symptoms, diagnosis, and therapy of primary sarcomas of the pulmonary artery. <em>Thorac Cardiovasc Surg</em> 1990;38(2):91–95.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1055/s-2007-1014001">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2190350/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Symptoms%2C+diagnosis%2C+and+therapy+of+primary+sarcomas+of+the+pulmonary+artery&amp;author=I+Kr%C3%BCger&amp;author=A+Borowski&amp;author=M+Horst&amp;author=ER+de+Vivie&amp;author=P+Theissen&amp;author=W+Gross-Fengels&amp;publication_year=1990&amp;journal=Thorac+Cardiovasc+Surg&amp;pages=91-95&amp;doi=10.1055%2Fs-2007-1014001&amp;pmid=2190350">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Grazioli V, Vistarini N, Morsolini M, et al. Surgical treatment of primary pulmonary artery sarcoma. <em>J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg</em> 2014;148(1):113–118.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtcvs.2013.07.054">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24075471/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Surgical+treatment+of+primary+pulmonary+artery+sarcoma&amp;author=V+Grazioli&amp;author=N+Vistarini&amp;author=M+Morsolini&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;journal=J+Thorac+Cardiovasc+Surg&amp;pages=113-118&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jtcvs.2013.07.054&amp;pmid=24075471">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mussot S, Ghigna MR, Mercier O, et al. Retrospective institutional study of 31 patients treated for pulmonary artery sarcoma. <em>Eur J Cardiothorac Surg</em> 2013;43(4):787–793.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/ejcts/ezs387">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22843511/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Retrospective+institutional+study+of+31+patients+treated+for+pulmonary+artery+sarcoma&amp;author=S+Mussot&amp;author=MR+Ghigna&amp;author=O+Mercier&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=Eur+J+Cardiothorac+Surg&amp;pages=787-793&amp;doi=10.1093%2Fejcts%2Fezs387&amp;pmid=22843511">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Rusthoven CG, Liu AK, Bui MM, et al. Sarcomas of the aorta: a systematic review and pooled analysis of published reports. <em>Ann Vasc Surg</em> 2014;28(2):515–525.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.avsg.2013.07.012">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24485779/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Sarcomas+of+the+aorta%3A+a+systematic+review+and+pooled+analysis+of+published+reports&amp;author=CG+Rusthoven&amp;author=AK+Liu&amp;author=MM+Bui&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;journal=Ann+Vasc+Surg&amp;pages=515-525&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.avsg.2013.07.012&amp;pmid=24485779">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">5.</div><div id="r5" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Blackmon SH, Reardon MJ. Pulmonary artery sarcoma. <em>Methodist DeBakey Cardiovasc J</em> 2010;6(3):38–43.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.14797/mdcj-6-3-38">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20834210/">PubMed</a></div><div class="